column168: On January 3, 2022, R+L Carriers (RLC) personnel at the above-referenced location discovered one (1) 55-gallon drum containing pentanols was damaged by adjacent cargo during transit. As a result, approximately eight (8) gallons of product released to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to perform the necessary corrective action. HCE personnel overpacked the damaged drum, then utilized absorbents to remediate the impacted surfaces.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: On January 3, 2022, facility personnel at the above-mentioned R+L Carriers (RLC) location discovered one (1) 330-pound tote containing corrosive liquid (ethanolamine/potassium hydroxide) was damaged by adjacent cargo during transit. As a result, approximately four (4) ounces of product released to the concrete loading dock. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LLC (ER) to perform the necessary corrective action. ER transferred all virgin product into a new tote, then deconstructed the damaged tote and utilized absorbents to remediate the impacted surface.
While in transit a pallet broke and caused a tear in a 50 lb. paper bag releasing 1 oz into trailer. Spill cleaned for proper disposal.

Terminal personnel placed a berm of absorbents in an effort to contain the release. The terminal was instructed to keep the area coned off. ERTS dispatched Rock Leaf Water Environmental (RLW) to the site to conduct cleanup operations. On January 6, 2022 at 0612 EST, RWL personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20 gallons of product released to a 20' x 20' area of the concrete dock floor. The product in the damaged tote was transferred into a new tote. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted area and collected. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all spent absorbents into (3) 55 gallon poly drums. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0730 EST, Allied personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4 gallons of product released to an 8' x 6' area of the trailer floor and a 3' x 4' area of the asphalt lot below. The damaged drum was placed into an 85 gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted area and collected. All spent absorbents were then collected into into (3) 55 gallon metal drums. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0410 ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics of a release of UN3261 "Daafit Plus" from 44 pound paper bags on the trailer. The cause was due to improper loading at the customers location. ERTS reviewed the SDS with terminal personnel and determined a contractor dispatch was needed. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1150 EST, EnviroServe personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 pounds of product released to a 5' x 3' area of the trailer floor. Two damaged bags were located and containerized along with all released product into a 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 1119 ET, XPO Logistics XLF notified ERTS of a 2 quart release of UN1993 "Nano2-CB-00002" from a 275 gallon tote due to improper loading, impacting the dock. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1358 ET, contractors arrived onsite and did not observe a release. The material and labeling were transferred to a new tote and the old tote was cut up and containerized with PPE waste and absorbent pads. All waste was placed into a 55 gallon poly drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics NRD reported trailer 465-3298 arrived with 4 cups of UN3267 "Versene 100" released from a 55 gallon poly drum that fell over in transit. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all cleanup operations. At 2115 ET, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2 gallons of product released to a 3' x 3' area of the trailer floor. The drum was secured for shipment onto the customer. Baking soda and water were then worked into the impacted area along with absorbents. All waste was then placed into a 30 gallon poly drum which was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

A leak was discovered on the bottom shell of the container during an inspection at Veolia's 10 day transfer facility. The leak was coming the drain line cam-lock cover. The leak consisted of a slow drip of liquid onto the ground. It is not known when the leak may have started. A drip pan was positioned under the leak until the leak was sealed. The container was then relocated from the transfer facility and was received for disposal at the Veolia Port Arthur TX facility. The area affected by the leak was remediated by a customer hired cleanup team.

column168: SequenceEvent: AM sort, while unloading trailer, pkg was removed from rear of trailer. The pkg had apparent signs of damage as it was wet from contents. I was called to assist, placed pkg inside red hazmat tote and brought to QA cage area. I used latex gloves to open pkg and see what had leaked and how. DescribePack: The top and right sides of cardboard are wet from alcohol. There is one corrugated liner on top of the four gallon bottles. Alcohol has soaked thru it as well. One cap was loose and you could visibly see alcohol on the bottle, at this time the alcohol begins to evaporate on the outer carton. I removed the cap to check seal, there is a thin silver seal under cap that wasnt completely adhered to bottle opening. I replaced the cap and tightened all four caps. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: I was able to tighten all caps and contain the spill, pkg currently placed inside salvage drum with bags and absorb material.

On 1-11-22 at 1400 personnel in the CSXT Edgewood Yard discovered UTLX662501, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine leaking from manway. The car was isolated and Georgia Pacific were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2022011100242). Hepaco LLC, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapors were being released from the manway and residue product on the side of the tank car. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tom Davidson at 404-376-9550. Contractor personnel found that 1 of 8 manway swing bolts not applied.  Manway was opened to inspect the gasket, after manway was opened no manway gasket was present.  A new manway gasket was installed.  Manway was closed and manway swing bolts were properly tool tightened.  Residue product on side of tank car was cleaned up and waste was containerized for disposal. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.

The covered hopper railcar was transported by the Union Pacific Railroad (UPRR) from Cheyenne, WY to Battle Mountain, NV.  Between 12/20/2021 and 12/21/2021 it was loaded with 219,600 lbs. of ammonium nitrate fertilizer (AN) and had a gross weight of 282,600 lbs. The railcar was inspected and the bottom gate was locked. The railcar departed Cheyenne on 12/27/2021 and was delivered to the Battle Mountain, NV site on 1/7/2022. The car remained at the Dyno Nobel rail siting until 1/10/2022, when it was moved to the rail scale. Employees noted a gross weight of 206,800 lbs. and observed the B side compartment was empty and the bottom end gate was open approximately ½-inch.  All of the seals were in place and unbroken. The employees inspected the tracks where the car sat between 1/7/2022 and 1/10/2022 and did not observe AN on or around the tracks.    The car traveled through WY, UT, and NV over an 11 day period and made stops in each State.  During transit, it appears the bottom end gate opened 1/2-inch spilling AN, which dispersed along the route within the railroad tracks until the compartment was empty.  It appears the bottom end gate lock failed to maintain the gate in the secured position.  Dyno Nobel is working with the UPRR to share information.  UPRR ordered their employees to inspect sites where the railcar was stopped and to look for signs of AN accumulation along the rail line between Cheyenne, WY and Battle Mountain, NV.  Dyno Nobel and UPRR have been providing information to the Nevada Department of Environmental Protection, the Nevada Public Utilities Commission, and the Federal Railroad Administration.  If an accumulation is located, Dyno Nobel will coordinate with UPRR to clean up the spill.    Dyno Nobel interviewed the railcar loaders and track crew, and reviewed hopper the car inspection checklist with those employees.

SequenceEvent: Package was given to me by an Ops Manager working on a van-line. The damaged package had been double bagged and put into a tote bin. CN transportation department employee reported liquid coming from the top of tank car UTLX 15960 (L / UN 1805 / Phosphoric Acid Solution) during switching operations at CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, La. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting liquid on exterior of the railcar near the combination housing.  The combination housing was secured by shipper seal.  The seal was removed.  Upon further investigation, the rupture disk (165 psi) was found to be blown and the rupture disk housing pin was not installed.  The vapor valve was partially open and the vapor plug was less than tool tight. Frangible disc was replaced and the rupture disk housing was properly secured. The vapor valve was closed and the plug was installed tool tight.  The product on car was neutralized. Tank car released for movement.

CN transportation department employee noted product leaking from the bottom outlet valve of tank car JRTX 11181(Residue / UN 1202 / Diesel Fuel) during switching operations at the CN Destrehan Yard, Destrehan Yard. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the bottom outlet valve handle was in the open position and a drip leak from the bottom outlet cap. The valve handle was closed and secured in the closed position with the pin.  The bottom outlet valve cap was tightened.  The railcar was released onto destination.

column17: GREAT WESTERN RAILWAY OF COLORADO, L.L.C.
column168: On 01/13/2022 FRA Hazmat Inspector J. Sedillo performed a visual inspection of GATX 200909 in Windsor, Colorado on the Great Western Railway (GWR) and noticed an odor coming from the top of the railcar near the liquid valve flange.  The Inspector notified the General Manager of GWR about the findings.  The GWR coordinated with the shipper, Veolia, to get a contractor to tighten three bolts on the valve to stop the release of vapor.  The railcar was a residue empty car that was shipped to GWR for storage purposes by Veolia.
column169: The shipper of the railcar needs to ensure that all valves are properly closed and all bolts are tool tight prior to offering the railcar for transportation.

column168: While preparing a shipment at Veolia's 10 day intrasit facility located in Fredericksburg, VA, an employee noticed an odor coming from the trailer.  Upon investigation, the employee identified a 55 gallon drum of Waste Flammable Liquids was leaking inside the trailer.  Four gallons are estimated to have spilled inside the trailer. The spill was contained to the trailer and the area has been cleaned. The leaking drum was overpacked for continued transportation to the disposal facility.  A nail was found on the trailer floor during clean up. It is believed that this caused the drum to be punctured causing the spill. There were no injuries.

column168: On 1/4/22, BNSF Portland IMF notified LARS of destination unit RDWY 142993 (billed LTL HAZ, UN 1263, Flammable Paint) which was observed to be leaking a white liquid during the de   ramping process. Upon inspection US Ecology observed a standard LTL shipment with multiple differentiating pieces of cargo unsecured. The unit was double stacked with very heavy hydraulic pumps on top and bottom, the cross members appeared to have failed in transit, allowing the pumps to land on the pumps below creating the shift. One of the pumps then punctured the paint buckets causing the leak. Totaling 13 damaged buckets, 5 were actively leaking, with approximately 10 gallons of paint of total loss. USE completed the adjustment by securing the pumps where they were to mitigate against additional damage, additionally they were not palletized and extremely heavy. Remaining buckets were re   palletized, and all the damaged buckets were secured in containers to prevent any additional leakage.

On 1/11/22, BNSF Portland IMF notified LARS of destination unit FDXU 533337 (billed HAZ of Liquid, N.O.S, Fungicide, UN 3082) that was observed to be leaking a white liquid after being deramped. The remediation of this unit was completed by US Ecology, it is estimated that approximately 65 total gallons leaked, 25 gallons in the lot, and 1   2 gallons made it into the storm drain catch basin (not drain line). The drain has been pumped and cleaned, along with the parking lot being washed. Unit was placed in the Facilities Safe Haven/ Haz Pit for containment. USE has determined the cause to be an unsecured double stacked crate that was able to migrate and landed on top of the tote below causing damage and penetrating it allowing the continence to leak out.

column168: On January 8, 2022, Loaded Tank Car UTLX 952043 (UN 1265 Pentanes) was found leaking liquid from the protective housing. Ice was forming around the housing and a few feet down the side before the product evaporated. When the Hazmat contractor inspected the car they found that there was no security seal on the protective housing pin and the liquid valve was partially open and the secondary cap was loose. The car was secured and released to destination.

column168: SequenceEvent: The package contained 2 x 1 gallon jugs of Dishmachine Detergent. It arrived to the station heavily stained and torn and upon further inspection one of the jugs was found to have leaked out of a loose cap, staining the other jug inside. DescribePack: The top of the outer packaging was torn open from the internal leakage. The inside of the box was heavily stained, as were the outer ridges and the bottles themselves. No packing material DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Upon discovery the package was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further containment and processing.

SequenceEvent: Package was unloaded and sent to QA where it was placed in a plastic drum for further inspection DescribePack: Package had loose caps DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: placed in plastic drum

SequenceEvent: The damaged package was placed in a hazardous material tote and taken to the hazardous material staging area away from personnel and other packages. DescribePack: Upon inspection it was noted that the plastic cap was cracked on the jug of phosphoric acid mixture causing the contents to leak. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The damaged package was placed in a hazardous material pail awaiting disposition.

SequenceEvent: Package was discover in preload at 6:00am. All package handlers were removed from area, QA did in house clean up. DescribePack: Shipper didn't provide enough inner packaging causing 1 liter bottle of acetic anhydride to break out of 4. SequenceEvent: Package was found leaking- uncertain how damage occured. it looks as though it had ben mishandled.  due to leak internally, parcel was placed in an uline plastic bag then placed in a tote and brought to the hazmat cage for inspection. DescribePack: Package did not fail- internal damage done to cans being transported- strong indication of mishandling. dents on all sides of each can in package- seals compromised due to damage from dents. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: positioned the hazmat upright- placed into uline bag to contain any run off.

SequenceEvent: FOUND BOX AND HAD WRITTEN ON IT THAT IT WAS LEAKING. OPENED THE BOX AND CONFIRMED THAT THE CONTENT WAS LEAKING. THE CAP WAS LOOSE, BUT THE BAND WASN'T BROKEN. WE PERFORMED THE INSPECTION OF THE DAMAGE, DERTERMINED A VERY LITTLE AMOUNT LEAKED OUT OF THE CONTAINER AND THEN PERFORMED THE DPR. DescribePack: FOUND THAT THE ETHYL CAP WAS LOOSE AND LEAKING. DurationRel: 12 and MitigateEffect: WE RETIGHTENED THE CAP ON THE ETHYL BOTTLE AND RE TAPED THE BOXS CLOSED.

column168: 01/24/22 at 17:31 hours, It was reported to H/M Scoons that in Selkirk Yard QG 15 terminal personnel had  discovered TILX400558, a residue tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and NGL Supply Terminal CO LLC, NYS DEC and NRC were notified.  (CHEMTREC 2022-01-24-00234. CSX Hazmat Manager D. Scoons, Responded to the scene along with personnel from HEPACO and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon claiming the railcar and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the liquid line valve was open and the secondary securement plug was installed but was not tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper John Houser 518-378-9794. H/M Scoons closed the liquid line valve and tightened the secondary plug. The leak was secured and the car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.
column169: (NAR code:119 5 What Failed: Liquid Line / Liquid Valve Where Failed: Closure plug Why Failed: Less than tool tight, valve open)

column168: On 01/04/2022, Landstar notified ERTS of a cargo release of UN3109 Microtox Prime.  ERTS contacted Hepaco out of Birmingham, AL to respond to confirm product and amount released. The Hepaco supervisor arrived on site at 1820 ET, he inspected the trailer and confirmed one tote was damaged. The name of the product is Microtox Prime out of a 318 gallon tote and appeared to be half empty. Of the 150 gallons of product that spilled approximately 100 spilled out onto the parking lot of the truck stop in a 20' x 5' area. The tote is punctured and appears to still be actively leaking. The crew began deploying absorbents on the parking lot and unloading the trailer. They performed a transfer for the tote that was damaged.  3-55 gallon poly drums were generated containing oil dry used to clean the release. Hepaco departed the site with the waste and will handle disposal.

column168: On 01/07/2022 at 2037 ET, Landstar notified ERTS of a cargo release containing UN1866 COR61-AA-565 “DCPD Laminating Resin”.  ERTS dispatched EnviroServe out of the Denver office to conduct the clean up and confirm amount released. At 1000 EST on 01/08/2022, EnviroServe located a small area on the ground measuring 6" x 6" where the product impacted the asphalt.  EnviroServe unloaded each drum and inspected them each and stated the impacted drum was in the nose of the trailer. Enviroserve located the source of the release, the Impacted drum had two cracks on the bottom of the drum due to the integrity of the metal. EnviroServe estimated 5-8 gallons of product was lost to the trailer floor. Enviroserve has overpacked the impacted drum and is wiped down the bottoms of the adjacent impacted drums. 1-110 gal overpack DF containing the damaged drum, and 1-55 gallon DM containing impacted PPE was generated and taken off site by EnviroServe to handle proper disposal.

THE RESPONDER RESPONDED TO A CALL REGARDING A SPILL. WHEN THEY PULLED UP THE BELT WAS OFF AND THE BOX WAS NOT MOVED BY ANYONE. ONCE THE BOX WAS IDENTIFIED AS A DECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, THE RESPONDER PROCEEDED TO LOOK THROUGH THEIR DECISION TREE AND FOLLOWED THE CORRESPONDING STEPS REGARDING THE PACKAGE. THERE WAS NO VISIBLE LEAKING LIQUID SO THE RESPONDER GRABBED THE PACKAGING AND PUT IT INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY AND RESTARTED THE BELT. ONCE THE PACKAGE WAS SAFELY PUT ONTO THE COFFIN PITO CART, IT WAS TAKEN BACK TO THE PSC FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column42: ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL OR ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, WITH MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: EMPLOYEE FOUND HAZMAT PACKAGE AND WAS ABLE TO SMELL PRODUCT THROUGH PACKAGE. A RESPONDER WAS CALLED, AND THE PACKAGE WAS TAKEN BACK TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. UPON OPENING UP THE PACKAGE AND INSPECTING IT, IT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING AND SMELLED STRONGLY, SO MY RMP PLACED A BAG AROUND IT AND IN A SPILL TUB ON A RESPONDER CART AND MOVED IT OUTSIDE AND PLACED A CONE BY IT WHILE I LOOKED UP THE SDS. THE SDS STATED THE PRODUCT WAS FATAL IF INHALED. ONE OF THE RESPONDERS NEARBY, NOTED THAT SHE HAD DEVELOPED A SCRATCHY THROAT AFTER BEING EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT'S FUMES. AFTER REMOVING HERSELF TO SOME FRESH AIR, SHE FELT BETTER AND DECLINED MEDICAL TREATMENT.

PACKAGE WAS REPORTED AS A LEAKER AT THE YELLOW UNDER SLIDE. UPON ENTRY TO THE AREA OF LEAKED PACKAGE I OBSERVED THE HAZMAT MARKINGS AND DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL. WEARING PROPER PPE AND FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE I OBSERVED THE PACKAGE WAS WET ON THE BOTTOM HALF. I CONTAINED THE PACKAGE IN A YELLOW SPILL TUB, CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE AND BROUGHT THE DAMAGED PACKAGE TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING.

SequenceEvent: Package was unloaded from trailer and sent down NC belt to tugger line, where it was loaded into a cart and brought to van line for loading. Package was likely crushed while staged on induct rollers or may have fallen off conveyor at end of belt.  Package was not van-scanned by Loader or loaded onto delivery vehicle. Wet package was placed in a plastic tote and brought to QA cage for inspection. DescribePack: Bladders have stem-style closure for product to be used in wall dispenser. column168: A PACKAGE CAR DRIVER CAME TO MY CO-WORKER AND I AND TOLD US THAT HE HAD A CORROSIVE IN HIS PACKAGE CAR. HE SAID THAT THE CUSTOMER REFUSED THE PACKAGE BECAUSE IT WAS A RE-BOXED SIX PART HAZMAT THAT WAS "PROBABLY" LEAKING, THEY ALSO TOLD HIM THAT THIS HAPPENS FREQUENTLY. SO MY CO-WORKER GRABBED EVERYTHING SHE NEEDED TO CLEAN IT UP AND BRING IT BACK TO THE HAZMAT COMPLIANCE CENTER FOR FURTHER INSPECTION. THE PACKAGE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE LEAKING. HOWEVER WHEN I OPENED THE PACKAGE TO SEE WHAT WE HAD GOING ON THE INSIDE, THERE WAS THE ORIGINAL PACKAGE INSIDE OF A PLASTIC BAG. THE ORIGINAL BOX HAD BEEN LEAKING. IT LOOKED LIKE A BOTTLE OR TWO HAD A LOOSE CAP BEFORE SOMEONE DECIDED TO JUST TIGHTEN THE CAPS, BAG THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, AND THEN RE-BOX IT AND SEND IT OUT TO THE CUSTOMER. USING ALL THE PROPER UTENSILS, THE LEAKER WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE HAZMAT COMPLIANCE CENTER.

I RESPONDED TO A HAZMAT LEAKER ON DOOR 72 IN UNLOAD. UPON ENTERING TRAILOR I NOTICED THE HAZMAT HAD BEEN MOVED. IT WAS LEAKING ONTO THE FLOOR AND ON A FEW OTHER PACKAGES. I COULD ALSO TELL IT HAD BEEN SET UPSIDE DOWN WITHIN A SHORT TIME FRAME FROM WHEN I RESPONDED TO IT. I ABSORBED THE SPILL, TOOK THE HAZMAT AND LEAKED ON PACKAGES BACK TO CLERK AREA FOR PROCESSING. UPON INSPECTION I FOUND THAT THE LEAK HAD RESULTED FROM LOOSE LIDS AND BEING PLACED UPSIDE DOWN.
UNDETERMINED

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET/STAINED IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER IN SECTION-C. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 1 MINUTE A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 5 LITER JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/4 OF A ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 10 OZ OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE LOWER SIDE WALLS AND BOTTOM OF CARTON. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A 2-SECTION HOSPITAL DISINFECTANT 2 EACH OF PARTS "A"   "B" AND IT WAS THE NON-REGULATED "B" PRODUCT THAT LEAKED. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A DOUBLE BOX 2 CORRUGATED CONFIGURATION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

THE HAZ-MAT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE EARTH CITY, MO UPS HUB, AT 17:30, ON AN IRREG TRAIN CART AT THE IRREG SORTING AREA. AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER (A 5 GALLON CLOSED HEAD PLASTIC BUCKET) REVEALED A SMALL PUNCTURE ON THE SIDE OF THE BUCKET NEAR THE BOTTOM. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILLAGE WAS HUMAN ERROR IN THE HANDLING OF THE PACKAGE. THE IRREG SORTER SWUNG THE BUCKET, INSTEAD OF LIFTING IT, AND HIT THE CORNER OF THE METAL IRREG CART CAUSING THE PUNCTURE. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED, CONTAINED, AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA FOR DISPOSAL. ALL MATERIAL HAS BEEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.

SequenceEvent: After package was transported to vanline, package handler with radio informed QA of a potentially "leaking" package. QA Admin went to retrieve package and noticed that it had hazardous marking on it. The package was placed in a bin and carried back to QA area before informing other Admin with more Hazmat experience. When inspected, the box was found wet but not actively leaking; the cap on the inner bottle was loose with no seal under it. There was also no packing material in the box. DescribePack: The cap on the bottle was not properly tightened, and there was no seal under it. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed in a bin and moved to safer location to be handled by an employee with more Hazmat training and experience.

SequenceEvent: The package contained 4 x 1 gallon jugs of Ecotemp Phase 1 Detergent. It arrived to the station stained and torn open and upon discovery it was placed in a hazmat bag and bin and brought over to damages for further containment and processing. DescribePack: The outer packaging was heavily stained in one corner/side, ripping from the damage. The inner packaging was stained in the same area right around one of the caps of the jugs, and there is evidence of staining on the jugs as well. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Upon discovery the package was placed in a hazmat bag and bin for further containment and processing.

column168: SequenceEvent: ITEMS FROM PACKAGE AND LABEL WERE FOUND AT 619-CHAM IN A SALVAGE DRUM AMONGST OTHER DRUMS FROM OTHER LOCATIONS THAT NEEDED DISPOSAL. THERE WAS A PRINTOUT OF A HESS COMODOTY INFORMATION ENTRY INCLUDED, HOWEVER DOES NOT APPEAR THAT HESS ENTRY WAS SUBMITTED, NOR ISF OR DPR DONE, AND LAST SCAN ON PACKAGE WAS A RELABLE AT RKIS FACILITY. COPYING SPILL INFO FROM PRINTOUT, THEIR WRITING FOR EACH SECTION WILL BE IN QUOTES: "IT FELL OFF THE IC LINE AND SPILLED SOME FROM A LOOSE CAP". I HAVE ENTERED ISF AND DPR NOW. DescribePack: "THE LID STARTED LEAKING AFTER A DROP DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: "ABSORBENT PADS AND A REPACK"
PACKAGE WAS IN DMP CAGE IN SPILL TRAY. RESPONDED TO PACKAGE USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS. PROCESSED PACKAGE.
THE RESPONDER RESPONDED TO THE LEAKING HAZMAT AND CLEANED IT UP FOLLOWING THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. HE THEN TRANSPORTED IT BACK TO THE DMP ARE FOR PROCESSING.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY A PRIMARY SORTER IN SECTION-E. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE CUT THE POWER ON THE BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 4 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 20 LITER PLASTIC BLADDER WAS SLIGHTLY LOOSE, CAUSING APPROX. 8 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 200 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.
ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED. NO NEUTRALIZER WAS ADDED TO THIS SPILL.

column168: CN Mechanical employee reported a strong irritating odor around NATX 400679 (R / Petroleum gas, Liquefied / UN 1075 / Class 2.1) at CN Mays Yard, Harahan, La.  The railcar was isolated, all notifications made.  CN response team responded and when walking close to the railcar, an audible sound could be heard coming from the protective housing.  Upon opening the protective housing, all the valves were checked.  The vapor valve was found to be partially opened.  When the vapor valve was closed.  The plug was checked and found to be tool tight, but still allowed vapors to escape.  The plug was removed, threads cleaned and thread sealant tape applied and reinstalled tool tight. The railcar was released onto destination.

column42: AEROSOLS, POISON, PACKING GROUP III (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE INSIDE THEIR PACKAGE CAR. THEN PLACED THE BOX INSIDE TWO DRIVER RELEASE BAGS AND FINISHED THEIR ROUTE. WHEN DUSTIN RETURNED TO THE BUILDING THEY BROUGHT LEAKING PACKAGE TO THE CLERKS' STATION AT 19:55. THE CLERK THEN CALLED FOR A RESPONDER WHO BROUGHT THE BOX BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA FOR PROCESSING. WHEN THE RESPONDER OPENED THE BOX HE SAW AN EMPTY AEROSOL CAN AND THE BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY HAZARDOUS MARKINGS.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, PALED AND SPLIT TO THE NORTH SORT AISLE. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PLACED ON THE BOTTOM SLIDE. THE CLERK ON THE BOTTOM SLIDE NOTICED THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING. HE IMMEDIATELY LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR THEN CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER, FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PLACED IN A LINED SPILL TUB. THE EQUIPMENT WAS CLEANED FOLLOWING THE DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. AN SDS SHEET WAS OBTAINED SHOWING IN SECTION 14 THE PACKAGE WAS A LIMITED QUANTITY. THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP

column168: Driver loaded up 5 drums of material. Driver properly secured them in the back of the vehicle after inspecting them to ensure they were in shippable condition. Driver put on his PPE, and entered the back of the truck. Driver located the leaking drum, and upon inspection, found a gash in the body of the drum near the bottom chime. Driver tripped the drum over to prevent any more material from leaking out. Driver used absorbents to clean up the spilled material. A Clean Harbors field service crew was dispatched to assist in the clean up. Once all the liquid was absorbed, the drum was placed in a proper salvage drum, and closed to manufacture's specifications. The clean up material was placed in an appropriate container, and closed to manufacture's specifications. No drains, water ways, or soil was impacted from this release.

A COMAT article UN1066 reservoir assembly (lavatory extinguisher) was discovered to in the bottom of the transport package underneath the internal packing material and flew undeclared. This article was included in the same package that was properly declared for a separate, but similar article.    On 1/9, while processing parts, agent processed MPN: 40400-2 (FTN 41IGM5). When part was processed this MPN through GEM, agent received an install error. Agent then went to ZDSI and saw it was moved into 1414. Agent then moved the part into 1416 and processed the install only.  While waiting for the paperwork, agent placed the box with the part in it on the shelf.   On Monday, 1/10, agent processed out the removed part (FTN: 66II2V), agent decided to change the box out, as the old one had a hole in it. While getting ready to break down the box, agent found a second unit underneath all the padding. Agent then researched the part and saw that it was in MSP stock. Agent called over to MSP who told me that part was sent to the Vendor and the agent forgot to hit Post Goods. Agent then looked at the paperwork and saw the repair order still attached.   The box came from ATL on January 3, as a hard ground on DL491 on AWB 81332613 for AC688.

column168: Driver had just started off loading compartment #4 from cargo tank to customer storage tank via air compressor when he notice product leaking from QRB (Quick Release Bonnet) clamp resulting in approximately 1 gallon spill on to ground. Driver shut down procedure and placed a bucket underneath QRB then drained enough product to unhook three 20' hoses from Cargo tank to customer tank. After unhooking, driver walked over to what he thought was a containment drain and dumped approximately 4 gallons of product in drain. Moments later, driver started draining transfer hoses into drain totaling approximately 6 gallons into drain before plant personnel told him to stop because the drain was not containment, but a storm drain that lead to a fresh water source. Upon further investigation,  it was discovered that the main drain valve to main hole that leads to fresh water source was closed, therefore, product was not released into fresh water supply. Additionally, it was discovered that the QRB clamp did not fail, simply not properly tightened.  Plant personnel & driver began cleaning up spill, but the decision was latter made to call in a 3rd party environmental crew to clean up approximately 200' of drain line leading to main release valve.
column169: Driver has been retrained on stop work authority and the proper procedures for handling spill/issues at customer locations. Driver was also counseled on proper communication efforts with customer prior to starting the unloading process. Recommendation to plant personnel was to mark the there storm drain located within the designated unloading area as "No Dumping" and add a drain blocker cover to the unloading process prior to off-loading to seal the storm drain.

column168: 01.20.2022 – a US Ecology driver was at Kaiser Aluminum in Kalamazoo. He was preparing to making load spent 50% Sodium Hydroxide at the Kaiser Aluminum facility, which would be transported for beneficial reuse at the US Ecology North Facility in Detroit. The customer procedures stated the hose was not to be charged until the driver made a connection to the truck and gave a signal that he was ready. The process takes two employees from the customer site – (1) in the basement to start the pump, and (2), another at the main floor level to communicate with the driver and open the valve. After investigation, the valve was found to be partially opened, and the pumps were started prematurely. Material was pushed through the line to the truck. Material sprayed the USE Taylor driver, hitting his face, getting in his mouth and on his clothes. The driver was not wearing his proper PPE (face shield & chemical suit) yet at the time of this incident. The US Ecology driver received assistance from the customer site, flushing with water for approximately 15 minutes. The driver contacted US Ecology Health and Safety who intern consulted with an on-call medical service. The driver was able to leave the customer site and return to Taylor without further care or treatment
column169: US Ecology Taylor EHS conducted an investigation of the events. Kaiser Aluminum was contacted and participated by providing and discussing the protocols for loading trucks at their facility. It was determined that the protocols were not not followed by the employees, i.e., the valve at the fill connection was not checked, and PPE protection was not in place. It was agreed that training will be conducted and reviewed on the filling process to ensure these protocols are followed. Additionally, Kaiser Aluminum will not start the pumps or open any valves until the driver has indicated that he has made the proper connections. The process has been reversed connecting the hose to the truck prior to connecting the hose to the plant source.

column168: Shipper (Beckman Coulter) provided freight and documentation to Expeditors to move shipment via Air to Shanghai, China.  Shipper advised freight was non-hazardous.  Freight and documents were provided to airline carrier (Air China) for movement to destination as non-hazardous under MAWB 999-63307020 / HAWB 4200167725.  Freight traveled to Shanghai and was awaiting Customs clearance at destination.  A question was posed from destination to origin whether this freight should have been marked as hazardous.  The inquiry was made to the shipper and after additional research by the shipper, it was determined there was a systems error in Beckman Coulter's system that incorrectly showed the item number for these goods (B37829 Armstrong A-271B) as "non-hazardous".  Beckman Coulter has confirmed that their system has been updated effective immediately to show item B37829 Armstrong A-271B as "hazardous" UN2259 Triethylenetetramine, Class 8, II.  All future shipments of this item will be moved as hazardous.
column169: Beckman Coulter's system has been updated effective immediately to show item (B37829 Armstrong A-271B) as "hazardous" UN2259 Triethylenetetramine, Class 8, II.  All future shipments of this item will be moved as hazardous.  Corrective Action form from the Shipper is attached (signed by Mitch Marx of Beckman Coulter).    Expeditors also re-trained the air export personnel handling Beckman Coulter shipments on the importance of watching for red flags of hidden dangerous goods.

column168: While conducting a walk-through of the Ingenium- Kent yard and waste storage areas the morning of 01/17/2022, an Ingenium technician discovered a leaking container inside of the storage trailer. The technician immediately identified the source of the leak and promptly took steps to stop the release. The spilled material was confined to the trailer and did reach the environment. The spilled material was removed from the trailer and the leaking container was overpacked into another CleanPak XL. Upon inspection and investigation, it was determined that the likely cause of the release was a puncture from a pallet nail.
column169: After a thorough internal investigation, Ingenium's Corrective Action Team issued the following corrective action in order to prevent a recurrence: The site's Location Manager conducted a complete review of pallet inspection procedures with Ingenium- Kent's staff. Pallet inspection procedures were reviewed with instruction being provided as to how to mitigate protruding nails. The staff was also directed to reject pallets that are unacceptable for transport.

column168: At approximately 10:30am cst an Amerigas employee was driving a bobtail down an 11% grade decline.  The employee stated he could not slow the vehicle down.  The vehicle picked up speed and the employee lost control of the vehicle.  This caused  the vehicle to roll over onto its side. The vehicle slid approximately 60', striking a street sign and tree before sliding over the side of the edge of the road.  The vehicle slid down the embankment, rolled over multiple times and came to rest about 75' off the road. The vessel separated from the frame of the vehicle, the contents of the vessel stayed intact with just a very minor release of product from an internal valve on the rear of the vehicle.  After walking back up the hill the employee called 911 and explained what had happened. The road was cordoned off while the wrecker company removed the bobtail. In the process of recovering the bobtail, the internal valve broke, completely emptying out the vessels' product.  This was approximately 2550 gallons of propane.  There were no homes within the area and no environmental damage from this incident. The vessel was removed at approximately 2:30am and the frame of the vehicle was retrieved at 5:30am.  Both parts of the bobtail were taken to the wrecker storage yard for further investigation.
column169: The employee will complete Smith System training and a in house LMS course on bobtail rollover prevention.

column168: Package was offered to the spill cleanup specialist at our Pacheco CA location. Package was seen to have a spill coming from bottom of fiberboard box containing UN 1197. Inspection of the package found a glass bottle placed in a fibreboard box. Glass bottle was placed in a plastic moisture barrier and surrounded by starch packing peanuts for dunnage. During transit and before delivery to final destination, glass bottle inside of package broke and allowed for entirety of contents to spill out. Package placed in salvage drum and Consignee contacted for disposition of package.

Driver was traveling south on Hwy 13 at mm 65 during inclement weather when the truck left the roadway. While attempting to negotiate truck back onto the roadway the truck rolled. The trailer was compromised and began to leak jet fuel out of the front compartment on the Left side. The release of the product was stopped by the Colorado hazmat response team shortly after the accident with the majority of the cargo being safely recovered by transferring to another trailer and transported back to our Garnd Junction Colorado yard.  We don't feel this accident met the requirement to report to the NRC as it did not meet any of the listed criteria in 49 CFR 117.15; however, a phone report was made to NRC by other party so we are therefore completing the 5800.1 report.
column169: Work with employees companywide on highway risk factors that cause rollover accidents through videos and safety meetings. We will also cover unsafe driving behaviors such as winter driving, fatigue, and complacency. We will also remind all employees that "Stop work authority" Is available whenever an unsafe condition or act could result in and unwanted event. Making this a part of regular training will help remind drivers to always be in attention when behind the wheel.

Pan Am Railways train P0-4 derailed due to a crew member failed to take the derailment switch off. (Cause Man Failure) Two LPG tank cars came off the track and tipped upside down. One of the LPG Tank Cars # MTZX 330053 was releasing a small amount of vapor from the protrctive housing area at approximatel six feet away from the protective housing no vapors were found. Local fire responded along with the Pan Am Railways Safety Dept., Both agencies monitored the release until the car was uprighted. At that time both agencies went on to the top of the tank car to check damages and the release, No damages or release was noted at that time. The tank car was moved to the customer who inspected the tank car and noted no damages to the components under the protective housing. The amount of vapor release was so minor that the customer also confirmed that they were able to unload all of the LPG product and states that they lossed no product from the result of the derailment. Addional Information: Part II #25 was not completed. after inspecting the rail tank car their was no known failure or defects to be able to determine why the rail tank car release the small amount of Vapor. PART

column168: ERTS received a request to facilitate cleanup of a trailer that was reported to be transporting empty drums. While unloading the drums, the vehicle operator noticed residual liquid on the trailer floor that was presumed to be from drums that were left at the customers location before relocating to a nearby Loves Travel Stop. Upon contractor arrival at the involved trailer, the trailer was empty and residual liquid was observed on the trailer floor. The responding contractor utilized clay absorbent material to address residual product observed.  The spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum.  The waste drum was then transported by Allied International Emergency to  Abilene Environmental Landfill in Abilene, Texas for proper disposal.
